      <string id="gpupdate_drive_maps_name">Name of the machine's network drive mount directory</string>
      <string id="gpupdate_drive_maps_name_help">The policy allows you to specify the name of the symbolic link to the machine's network drive mount directory

If the policy is disabled or not configured, the default symbolic link name is set as follows:

/media/gpupdate/{drives.system} — for system network drives and /media/gpupdate/.{drives.system} — for hidden system network drives.

When the "Display machine's network drives in the home directory" policy is enabled, the symbolic link name is set as follows:

~/net.{drives.system} — for system network drives and ~/.net.{drives.system} — for hidden system network drives.

Note: {drives.system} is the default value that points to the disk being connected, replace it with the actual name without curly braces.

      </string>
      <string id="gpupdate_drive_maps_name_user">Name of the user's network drive mount directory</string>
      <string id="gpupdate_drive_maps_name_user_help">The policy allows you to specify the name of the symbolic link to the user's network drive mount directory

If the policy is disabled or not configured, the default symbolic link name is set as follows:

/run/media/USERNAME/{drives} — for user network drives and /run/media/USERNAME/.{drives} — for hidden user network drives.

When the "Display user network drives in the home directory" policy is enabled, the symbolic link name is set as follows:

~/net.{drives} — for user network drives and ~/.net.{drives} — for hidden user network drives.

Note: {drives} is the value that by default points to the connected drive, replace it with the current name without curly braces.

      </string>
      <string id="gpupdate_drive_maps_home_disable_net">Network drive mount directory name prefix</string>
      <string id="gpupdate_drive_maps_home_disable_net_help">This policy allows you to disable the "net." prefix in the names of symbolic links to network drive mount directories

When the "Map machine network drives in the home directory" policy is enabled, the symbolic link name is set as follows:

~/net.{drives.system} — for system network drives and ~/.net.{drives.system} — for hidden system network drives.

When the "Map user network drives in the home directory" policy is enabled, the symbolic link name is set as follows:

~/net.{drives} — for user network drives and ~/.net.{drives} — for hidden user network drives.

If the policy is disabled or not configured, the names of symbolic links to mount directories begin with the prefix "net."

The "net." prefix is ​​removed from the link names depending on the selected options.

      </string>
      <string id="UserPolicyMode">Configure user Group Policy loopback processing mode</string>
      <string id="UserPolicyMode_Help">This policy setting directs the system to apply the set of Group Policy objects for the computer to any user who logs on to a computer affected by this setting.
It is intended for special-use computers, such as those in public places, laboratories, and classrooms, where you must modify the user setting based on the computer that is being used.

By default, the user's Group Policy Objects determine which user settings apply.
If this setting is enabled, then, when a user logs on to this computer, the computer's Group Policy Objects determine which set of Group Policy Objects applies.

If you enable this setting, you can select one of the following modes from the Mode box:

"Replace" indicates that the user settings defined in the computer's Group Policy Objects replace the user settings normally applied to the user.

"Merge" indicates that the user settings defined in the computer's Group Policy Objects and the user settings normally applied to the user are combined.
If the settings conflict, the user settings in the computer's Group Policy Objects take precedence over the user's normal settings.

If you disable this setting or do not configure it, the user's Group Policy Objects determines which user settings apply.
      </string>
      <string id="UserPolicyMode_Merge">Merge</string>
      <string id="UserPolicyMode_Replace">Replace</string>
